title: Yellen Expects Fed to Start Raising Rates This Year
description: In a speech, the central bank chairwoman said she thought weak growth during the first part of the year most likely reflected temporary disruptions.

title: Neighborhood Joint: Strange, Beloved, Local, Endangered: Five Years of the Neighborhood Joint
description: In a city of change, some small, beloved local establishments, like an ices stand in Queens and a place to buy octopus in Brooklyn, endure.

title: U.S.-Cuba Talks on Restoring Diplomatic Ties Stall
description: Representatives from both nations met at the State Department but emerged without a deal and only a promise to continue talking.

title: Young Saudis, Bound by Conservative Strictures, Find Freedom on Their Phones
description: Confronted with an austere version of Islam and strict social codes, they increasingly rely on apps and social media for self-expression and liberation.

title: ISIS Claims Responsibility for Bombing at Saudi Mosque
description: The attack on Shiites during midday prayers left at least 21 people dead on Friday, and some Saudis on social media rushed to blame Iran.

title: Overvalued in Silicon Valley, but Don’t Say ‘Tech Bubble’
description: The tech industry’s venture capitalists admit to a certain amount of “frothiness” in start-up investments, but they studiously avoid another word. Bubble.

title: Prospect of Hillary Clinton-Marco Rubio Matchup Unnerves Democrats
description: They are worried that Mr. Rubio, a son of Cuban immigrants, could win over Hispanic voters and that he would offer a sharp generational contrast.

title: Ireland Votes in Referendum on Same-Sex Marriage
description: If the yes campaign wins, the country would be the first to adopt gay marriage by a popular vote.

title: Police Shut Down Mosque Installation at Venice Biennale
description: Officials closed an art installation that was part of the 56th Venice Biennale, declaring it a security hazard.

title: Your Friday Briefing
description: Here’s what you need to know to start your day.

title: City Room: New York Today: See Forever, Weather Permitting
description: Friday: Hazy viewings, pleasant weather, and cookie secrets.

title: Memorial Day Travelers Unlikely to Be Deterred by Rising Gas Prices
description: AAA predicts that 33 million Americans will hit the road this weekend, the highest number for the holiday since 2005, despite creeping fuel costs.

title: Political Memo: Hillary Clinton, Acutely Aware of Pitfalls, Avoids Press on Campaign Trail
description: The news media is Hillary Rodham Clinton’s only real opponent so far en route to the Democratic nomination, and it makes political sense for her to avoid it.

title: First Draft: Today in Politics: No Time for a Lazy Summer as Campaigns Ramp Up
description: Good Friday morning from Washington, where the Senate still has some work to do, even if the House has already left for the holiday.

title: Italy’s Treasured Olive Oil, at the Source
description: In Tuscany and Puglia, making olive oil is a lifestyle, one threatened by bad weather and a killer bacteria.

title: Obama Set to Strengthen Federal Role in Clean Water Regulation
description: The administration is to soon announce new executive action that would restore its authority to limit water pollution. Republicans are trying to block the president.

title: The Bookstore Built by Jeff Kinney, the ‘Wimpy Kid’
description: Jeff Kinney has sold more than 150 million copies of his “Diary of a Wimpy Kid” books. Now he is opening a bookstore in his hometown.

title: Howard Johnson’s, an Orange-Roofed Symbol of a Bygone Era, Returns to Lake George
description: A businessman banking on a love of nostalgia recently reopened the country’s last orange-roofed HoJo’s in the Adirondacks town, evoking warm stories of the past among many local residents.

title: Lens Blog: When Every Day Is Memorial Day
description: Irked by how people treat Memorial Day like just another three-day weekend, Andrew Lichtenstein photographed military funerals for soldiers who died in Iraq.

title: Ex-Korean Air Executive in ‘Nut Rage’ Case Freed From Prison After Sentence Is Cut
description: Cho Hyun-ah, who forced a plane back to its gate over how she was served nuts, is released after an appeals court reduced and then suspended her sentence.
